  Started resource 'apachegroup' prefers node 'rocky-node2' with score INFINITY. How to clear this constaint

That line:

Started resource 'apachegroup' prefers node 'rocky-node2' with score INFINITY

is a temporary (runtime) constraint created by Pacemaker (called a cli-prefer constraint). You need to remove it explicitly.


Run:

pcs constraint --full

You will see something like:

Location Constraints:
  Resource: apachegroup
    Enabled on:
      rocky-node1 (score:100)
      rocky-node2 (score:INFINITY) (id: cli-prefer-apachegroup)

👉 Note the ID (example: cli-prefer-apachegroup)



Started resource 'apachegroup' prefers node 'rocky-node2' with score INFINITY
⚠️ Important (to avoid it coming back)

This constraint was auto-created due to manual move or failover behavior.

To prevent it again:

✔ Set stickiness
pcs resource defaults resource-stickiness=1000

OR stricter:

pcs resource defaults resource-stickiness=INFINITY
🧠 Why this happens

Whenever you run:

pcs resource move apachegroup

Pacemaker creates this:

cli-prefer-apachegroup (INFINITY)

👉 It stays until you clear or delete it

✅ Alternative shortcut (easier)

Instead of finding ID, you can run:

pcs resource clear apachegroup

👉 This will:

Remove all temporary constraints
Clean fail counts
Reset placement
🚀 Recommended way (best practice)

Use this:

pcs resource clear apachegroup

✔ Simple
✔ Safe
✔ Removes all runtime constraints

